It is officially in the logbook. I have 2.3 flight hours ^_^
#TeaganAir
If I had to describe to you what it is like to fly a small plane, I would say it is a mixture of a motorcycle/quad and a boat 4,000 feet in the air.
On the ground, one is very fast immediately. It is all a bit unstable on the ground, hence motorcycle/quad.
And if you didn't know it yet: You steer a plane on the ground with your feet, not with the control stick. Rudder pedals and brakes. It's not a car.
In the air, it's wobbly, and you're floating a bit. It feels like you're in a boat on the water. You can steer it, but sometimes a wave comes and throws you off course a bit, so you have to get used to the swell, only in the air.
And yet another random detail:
Flying is physically demanding. Today, my back and legs hurt, as if I had been to the gym.
This is not like a Sunday outing with the car. It's more of a sport than a leisurely ride, in my recently gained opinion.
A nice Saturday, my loved ones. Welcome to 4,000 feet.
I'm going again tomorrow. Then we'll practice stalling and slow flying.
Today the weather was rough, but it was a lot of fun. We practiced slow flying and stalling. Once we had a ground speed of only 16 mph at a flying speed of 65.
It was a beautiful clear day, a bit foggy higher up, but still beautiful.
